================================================================================
PART 9: Boundary in difference-sequence representation
================================================================================

Paths from 0 are determined by difference sequence (d_1,...,d_m), d_i in S.
Vertex sequence: (0, d_1, d_1+d_2, ..., d_1+...+d_m) mod n.
Removing interior vertex i (1<=i<=m-1) merges d_i and d_{i+1}.
The resulting face starts at vertex 0 if i>0, or at vertex d_1 if i=0.
Wait — we also remove i=0 (first vertex) and i=m (last vertex)?
NO: for GLMY path homology, boundary only removes INTERIOR vertices.
Interior = positions 1,...,m-1 (for an m-path = (m+1)-tuple).

So: removing vertex at position i (1<=i<=m-1):
  - The face always starts at vertex 0 (shift=0)!
  - The diff sequence becomes (..., d_i + d_{i+1}, ...)
  - The face is STILL from vertex 0, so canonical = face itself!

WAIT. This means shift is ALWAYS 0 for GLMY boundary.
If shift=0, then phase = omega^{k*0} = 1 for ALL k.
So B_k = B_0 for ALL k?!

Let me verify this claim...

  Degree m=1:
    Shifts seen: []

  Degree m=2:
    All shifts are 0 => B_k = B_0 for all k at this degree

  Degree m=3:
    All shifts are 0 => B_k = B_0 for all k at this degree

  Degree m=4:
    All shifts are 0 => B_k = B_0 for all k at this degree

  Degree m=5:
    All shifts are 0 => B_k = B_0 for all k at this degree

  Degree m=6:
    All shifts are 0 => B_k = B_0 for all k at this degree

